text: There is a clock on the wall at the hospital here that says something like: "LET'S MAKE THE WORLD A BETTER PLACE." and every time I pass by it I imagine Dr. Fauci looking down benevolently at me and guiding me on my path.

One funny thing about being a somewhat open person is you are deprived of anonymity. E.g. I go to the park and the usual cardio runners know me because I make small talk to them, I go to the store and guard and employees all know me. You're never an empty face, can't "disappear".

Even if I go to some small part of the town on the other end of the outskirts it will still be useless because in a week or so I'll just end up knowing everyone again and not feel like a nameless stranger

The fundamental idea that Leibniz fought was that the universe is unknowable and man must give up and live like an animal because he has no hope to understand it anyways, as he sees only surfaces. Infinitesimals, Leibniz's law of continuity, monads were all weapons in this war...

The opposite line of thinking is that the world is composed of vague bodies we can measure and dissect, but never penetrate into. Atoms are hard and indestructible, but moands are philosophical units, intended to show the same laws of reason that govern the visible scale down too

I guess if we're using Dr. Ray Peat's concepts, it's easy to see this as a sort of intellectual learned helplessness, a worldview of the vagus nerve and Parasympathetic nervous system activity. Echoes of it end up even in like Deleuze and other later writers. Just believe urself.
